posts.name: Casey Brotherton
posts.cooked:
Hello,

I am a fan of the python script to extract dsevent/dslog from here:

Alternate viewer for Driver Station Logs (dslog)? Control System

Parse FIRST FRC driver station log files. Contribute to ligerbots/dslogparser development by creating an account on GitHub.

With the latest driver station, it seems that the log version changed to 4.  The python script seems to work with the new log version if I ignore version checking.

Anybody know where I can find change log or any information on version 4 logs/events?

Thanks, Casey

link_counts.title: Alternate viewer for Driver Station Logs (dslog)?

posts.name: Casey Brotherton
posts.cooked:
Here is what I am seeing so far:

dsevents looks the same between version 3 and 4.  By taking a small file, opening it in driverstation, and stepping through header, LV timestamp, LV string. It seems to match up.

The python script did not work for the dslog.  It read things in…but a few things were off:

Looking in Driverstation, the voltage seemed to range between 12.5 to 12.7 volts from what I could see.  The Robot was never placed into autonomous mode. Driver station also showed 24 PDP’s and all of them were noted as zero.

The python script though created a csv where auto was true, and voltage was all over the place.

I opened the log using od -ha, and looked for repeating patterns.

It seemed like after the 10 byte information of each line, there were 68 bytes before similar 10 bytes started repeating again.

My example dslog was 489470 bytes long.  With a 20 byte version/LV timestamp header, that left 48950 bytes that should be evenly divisible, and 48950/78=6275

If I change the python to assign 68 bytes to the PDP, it’s still not correct, as some of the PDP’s are showing values.

However the values for the first 10 bytes match with what would be reasonable for when the driver station was logging.

If I can get closer to what the format should be, I will open a pull request for the python script.

Thanks, Casey

posts.name: Alex
posts.cooked:
I did manage to somewhat figure out how the PDP/PDH values are encoded. You can find what I did here . But in summary everything is the same from version 3 except for this:

There are 4 bytes before the PDP values now, these lets us know the PDP type (the 3rd byte is 25 for CTRE, 33 for REV, and 0 for No PDP)

The PDP data encoding did not change for CTRE

The PDH data encoding for REV: The first 20 channels are encoded via 10 bit decimals (7.3), every 3 channels make up a 32 bit block (the last 2 bits in the block are ignored) except for channels 18/19 which are in a 24 bit block with the last 4 bits ignored. The last 4 channels (20/21/22/23) are each encoded in their own single byte (4.4) Unlike CTRE the REV PDH does not provide a voltage and resistance value And for some reason the REV PDH data is encoded with little-endian even though everything else is in big-endian…

The first 20 channels are encoded via 10 bit decimals (7.3), every 3 channels make up a 32 bit block (the last 2 bits in the block are ignored) except for channels 18/19 which are in a 24 bit block with the last 4 bits ignored.

The last 4 channels (20/21/22/23) are each encoded in their own single byte (4.4)

Unlike CTRE the REV PDH does not provide a voltage and resistance value

And for some reason the REV PDH data is encoded with little-endian even though everything else is in big-endian…

I think this is mostly right but, I only have tested it out on a few log files so far.

posts.cooked: Thanks for detailing the changes you found.  Gave it a quick try but before I could complete anything got caught up in another project.  Hoping to come back to this for after competition season.

posts.name: fovea1959
posts.cooked: Did you get back to this, or does it need digging into?

posts.name: Casey Brotherton
posts.cooked:
It was just so terrible that I abandoned it.

LabVIEW bit packing is uncomfortable to say the least. And I realized that even if I did figure things out. They could change in the next year.

I have leaned into high speed data logging this season, instead.

They have a utility to change it to csv, and the team controls the logging. Seems like a better win.

posts.name: fovea1959
posts.cooked: Good to know. I may still lean into it; we do high speed logging on the roboRIO, but some of the things we are looking for are in the DS logs, and being able to just pull them up without having to sftp into the roboRIO is a win.
